Holland Pouch Sew Along - Day 1

A few tips for today's cutting, basting, and quilting assignment:

If you're working with directional fabric, remember ro follow the instructions on page 11 to get everything facing the correct way.

I prefer to lengthen the stitch length on my machine  a little before quilting because it gives a more pronounced stitch line. You can play around with your machine's settings to see what you prefer.

After basting my layers together, I stitch a line through all three layers, about 1/8"-1/4" from one of the edges. Then, whenever possible, I start my quilting lines from that side. Even though it's already basted, this further helps the layers from shifting as they're quilted.

I use a Hera Marker and ruler to mark my quilting lines. The Hera Marker leaves an impression instead of an ink line. There are a lot of other great methods for marking (air or water erasable pens, tape, etc.) or there are some great organic quilting designs that don't need lines marked.

That's it for today! Any questions?

If you share progress photos of your Holland Pouch, remember to use the tag #hollandpouch so we can all find your post and cheer easch other on. 🥰

Holland Pouch Sew Along - Day 2

Today, we're prepping the Bindings and Handles. It's a pretty simple assignment, but I still have a couple tips/reminders to share.

When you attach the fusible interfacing to the Handles, remember to iron it to the *wrong* side of the fabric.

I often use coordinating thread to top stitch around the Handles, but thread in a fun, contrasting color also looks great!

That's it for today! Any questions?

Holland Pouch Sew Along - Day 3

Today we're attaching the Zipper Bindings and zipper. But don't worry, it's all just straight lines!

Make sure you sew the Zipper Bindings to the *lining* side first!

When attaching the zipper, orient it as shown in the pattern with the opening at the top and most of tye extra length at the bottom. This will help with attaching the second side of the zipper.

As you sew the zipper on, go slowly and stay about 1/8" away away from the edge of the Zipper Binding.  As the pressure foot gets close to the zipper pull, you can lower the needle, lift the pressure foot, slide the zipper pull past the pressure foot so it's out of the way, and continue sewing.

When attaching the second side of the zipper, line up the top and bottom raw edges of the quilted panel to be even on both sides of the zipper tape, then pin in place. Unzip the zipper as much as you can before sewing that second side. This is where the extra zipper length comes in handy, as you'll need to wrangle the quilted panel a bit to keep it out of the way of the presser foot.

That's it for today. Any questions?

Holland Pouch Sew Along - Day 4

Today we're sewing our pouch closed and making the boxy corners. A few tips:

Remember to turn the pouch inside out before sewing it closed. If you have a metal zipper, you'll need to use the hand wheel on your machine to gently guide your needle through the metal zipper teeth. If you use your foot petal while sewing over metal zipper teeth, the needle will break!

Trim the extra zipper length off after sewing the pouch ends closed. You won't want to use your nice fabric scissors for this step (I have an older rotary cutter reserved for things like this).

When marking the boxy corners, it's super important to measure from the End Binding seam (not the outside edge of the End Binding). This will ensure the boxy corner is symmetrical when it's sewn shut.

That's it for today. Any questions?

Holland Pouch Sew Along - Day 5

We're adding the handles and closing the boxy corners to finish our pouches today! 🎉 A few comments about today's assignment:

Not all sewing machines will handle the bulk well. If your machine is struggling to get through the layers, there are a few things to try:

Use the hand wheel on the side of your machine to gently guide the needle through the layers. 

After sewing the boxy corner closed (but before adding the binding), sew a few more lines through the boxy corner seam allowance. This will help flatten that section.

Grab a hammer or mallet (yes, you read that right) and pound on the boxy corner area - especially where the End Binding and Handle meet - to flatten it out.

The final seam on the Boxy Corner Bindings can be finished by hand (like a quilt binding). Hand finishing actually looks a lot cleaner and nicer, but as it takes longer and these bindings are on the inside of the pouch, I rarely do it.

That's it! Any questions?

Meet the Heartburst Mini Quilt Pattern set. Heartburst started out as a foundation paper piecing pattern, but I wanted to include an option for those that prefer traditional piecing, so instead of one mini quilt pattern this month, you get two! 🎉

Everyone that purchased the 12 Minis in 12 Months pattern bundle should have received the pattern set in your inbox this morning. For anyone else, you can find the pattern set in my Etsy shop. You'll receive two PDF downloads: one for the traditionally pieced heart (finishes at 8" x 8") and one for the foundation paper piecing heart (has 3", 6", 8", and 9" block options included).

Pattern: Heartburst Mini Quilt Pattern available in my shop (there's a link in my profile @centerstreetquilts).

#12minisin12months2023 #quilt #miniquilt #quilting #fpp #foundationpaperpiecing #heartquilt

Finish a Heartburst Mini Quilt with me! ❤️❤️❤️

1. Layer the backing, batting, and quilt block (you can baste with spray adhesive or safety pins).

2. Mark lines for quilting (I'm using a @cloverusa Hera Marker to make indentations, but erasable ink also works).

3. Pick a side where most of your quilting lines can start from. Sew down that side, 1/8" from the edge of the quilt block. This will keep your layers together and help minimize shifting as the lines are quilted.

4. Quilt away! For mini quilts, I like to do dense quilting, as it makes the mini quilt have more structure and evens out any wonkiness. I started out by marking and quilting lines 1" apart, then eyeballed quilting in between the 1" lines for lines 1/2" apart, then again quilted in between for quilting 1/4" apart. Phew! I usually just keep quilting until I'm happy with the density. 😆

5. Trim the layers even to the top quilt block.

6. Add binding. I used a 2 1/2" strip, folded and pressed in half. I sewed to the back first, then wrapped it around and attached to the front by machine. If hand finishing the binding, I'll attach to the front side first, then wrap around and hand sew to the back.

Any question? Please ask!

Pattern: Heartburst Mini Quilt Pattern (traditionally pieced) available in my shop.

Let's make the FPP version of Heartburst!

When making a foundation paper piecing quilt block, I like to remove the paper in any seams (right down the center on this block), but leave the rest of the paper on until I either sew it to other blocks, add borders, etc. or until I'm ready to quilt. The edges of fpp blocks often have fabric that's cut on the bias, so keeping the paper on until it's sewn to the border or neighboring blocks keeps those edges from stretching. 👍

Holland Duffle Sew Along Day 2

Today we're prepping the Bindings, Zipper Tabs, and Handles. A few tips for today's assignment:

❤️ Most of the Bindings just need to be pressed in half. Just watch for that first Zipper Binding that has slightly different pressing instructions to prep it for going on top of the pocket zipper.

❤️ The fusible interfacing for the Zipper Tabs isn't absolutely necessary, but I much prefer the extra weight the interfacing gives the Tabs. To try something different for the Zipper Tabs, the fabric + fusible interfacing combo can be substituted for a 4" long piece of webbing.

❤️ The Handles are written with a 1" wide strapping/webbing in mind, but you can definitely substitute a wider strapping if desired. If you're covering your strapping with fabric, adjusting the width of the Accent fabric Handle pieces will be necessary. Take the width of your strapping, double it, then add 3/4" to find the new wdth needed. For example, if using 1 1/2" wide strapping, you would need to cut the three WOF strips to 3 3/4" wide.

❤️ Using strapping without the fabric cover is a great option, too! For a cotton webbing you can zigzag the ends or turn them under to prevent fraying. For a polyester webbing, take a lighter or other small flame to gently melt and seal the edges.

Holland Duffle Sew Along - Day 3

With today's assignment, I feel like we're really getting into the construction of the duffle. Yay!!

A few tips and reminders for today:

❤️ Follow the instructions for the Pocket Bindings by first sewing them to the top of the LINING side of the quilted Pockets, then wrapping the Binding around the raw edge to the Main fabric side and top stitching into place.

❤️ After adding the zipper to the Zipper Pocket, place the top edge of the zipper tape into the fold of the Zipper Pocket Binding. Sew it into place, 1/8" away from the edge of the Binding, making sure you are sewing through the top layer of the Binding, the zipper tape, and the bottom layer of the Binding.

❤️ When the Zipper Pocket is finished, don't forget to trim the length to the size noted in the pattern! I actually forgot this step and had to unpick the Pocket from my Quilted Panel. 🙈

❤️ When attaching the sides of the Pockets to the Quilted Panel, I like to sew up each side separately, starting from the bottom of the Pocket and sewing up to the top of the Pocket (you can see this as I sew the Zipper Pocket onto the Quilted Panel in the video). When sewing multiple layers of fabric, it's easy for the top layer to shift and by sewing from the bottom up on both sides, the Pocket will shift in the same direction for each seam and result in a more symmetrical Pocket.

Any questions? 🥰

Holland Duffle Sew Along Day 4

Today is all about the Handles!

❤️ After getting the Handles situated on the Quilted Panel, I like to use a combination of pins and Wonder Clips to secure the Handles in place. 

❤️ A little bit of variation in the Handle length on each side won't be noticeable,  but as long as you lined up the end points and center of the Handles with the center of the Quilted Panel, the Handles should be pretty even.

❤️ Sew the Handles onto the Quilted Panel by sewing right on top of the previous stitch lines on the Handle. When you get to 1" above the Pockets, remember to backstitch several times over the horizontal stitch line to reinforce that seam.

Today, we're installing the zipper and closing the ends of the Duffle. A few tips and reminders:

❤️ Tuck the Handles into the Pockets to keep them out of the way for the last steps.

❤️ While installing the zipper, you'll need to wrangle the Quilted Panel a bit to keep everything lined up and out of the way of the needle. This is where the extra length in the zipper comes in handy! When sewing the second side of the zipper tape on, unzip the zipper as much as possible to allow for easier maneuvering.

❤️ After attaching the second side of the zipper tape, you can slide an extra zipper pull on the zipper tape to have a double zipper slide. It might take a couple times of threading the Pole onto the zipper teeth to get both sides of the zipper tape lined up correctly, but it's a fun edition to the Duffle.

❤️ Before sewing the ends of the Duffle closed, make sure you have the double turned inside out, and the zipper tabs are inserted.

❤️ If your sewing machine struggles going through the bulky areas, you can use your hand wheel to gently guide the needle through the layers or pull out a mallet or hammer to flatten those spots! Just be careful to stay away from the zipper teeth so you don't break them. 🔨

☀️ Sunny Side Up Sew Along Day 1 ☀️

Today, we're cutting everything out and quilting the panel. A few notes that might help:

☀️ Before quilting, we want to baste the layers to prevent shifting during quilting. I love to use Odif 505 basting spray for basting the layers of small projects like this, but safety pins also work great!

☀️ When marking lines for quilting, a Hera Marker is my preferred method (it makes an impression, not an ink mark). Erasable ink, tape lines, or a quilting guide attached to the presser foot are other great options to try.

☀️ I like how the standard foot on my sewing machine (Juki TL2000) handles machine quilting small projects, so I don't use a walking foot on this machine. However, I do prefer to quilt with a walking foot on my other machine (a Bernina). Do whatever works best for you!

☀️ Sewing a line down one side of the panel before quilting (1/8" away from the edge), then starting as many quilting lines as possible from that edge, will keep the layers from shifting.

☀️ After quilting and trimming the panel into a circle, remember to sew a quick line around the perimeter. This will help the cut edges of the quilting lines from coming undone and also keep the fabric edges from accidentally flipping the wrong way.

☀️ Make sure you sew the Hang Tab to the lining side BEFORE attaching the binding (notice how I forgot, so I had to unpick a little of the binding to add it in). 🤦‍♀️ 😆

☀️ Bias binding will be your best friend for sewing around curves! Since bias binding is cut on the diagonal (bias), there is a little stretch to it that allows it to be sewn to curves without bunching up or puckering. 🙌 When first attaching the bias binding to the lining side of your pouch, use a 1/4" seam and try not to stretch the binding as it is attached.

☀️ Watch the video to see how I like to join the binding ends for this pouch. I've found that if I sew one part at a time, the section where the bias binding begins/ends looks much smoother.

☀️ After flipping the binding around the raw edge of the quilted circle, top stitch just inside the edge of the binding fold to attach. Take your time with this step, as the top stitch seam will be visible.

Make a tiny vinyl zipper pouch with me! (save the video so you can find it later!) 🥰

You'll need:
🩷 A piece of vinyl
🩷 A zipper 12" or longer

🩷 Cut a piece of vinyl 7" x 12.5". This cute flower vinyl from @zippervalley is 12.5" long on the roll, so I just cut a strip 7" wide. Of course, you can adjust the size of the vinyl to fit your needs.

🩷 Cut a zipper about 12" long (you'll want it 4"+ longer than the shorter side of the vinyl). Add the zipper pull if it doesn't already have a pull on it. I'm using a size #5 zipper and a flower zipper pull (both from @zippervalley).

🩷 Sew the zipper to one of the short ends of the vinyl, right sides together. Flip the zipper right side up and fold the seam edge of the vinyl back on itself (wrong sides together) and away from the zipper. Top stitch along the edge of the vinyl to hold everything in place (you will be sewing through two layers of vinyl plus the zipper tape).

🩷 Line up the other short end of the vinyl with the other side of the zipper tape, right sides together, and sew the zipper to the vinyl making a tube. Turn the piece right side out, unzip the zipper as much as you can, and top stitch along the edge of the vinyl like you did in the last step (you want to turn the seam under and away from the zipper so you're sewing through two layers of vinyl plus the zipper tape).

🩷 Turn the piece wrong side out, orient the zipper so it's toward the top (pressing the right sides together to flatten the piece), and sew down both sides. Trim off the excess zipper tape (I'm using an old rotary cutter that I use for zippers, paper, etc.).

🩷 Turn the piece right side out. The heat from a hair dryer will help make the vinyl more pliable--but don't get your cutting mat too hot or it will warp. 🥴 A blunt tip stick can help get those corners pushed out all the way so they are nice and square.

🩷 Enjoy the cutest little vinyl zipper pouch!! 

This is the perfect simple project to get started with vinyl!! If you have any questions, please ask below and I'll do my best to answer them. 🥰

🩷 Essen Pouch Sew Along Day 1 🩷

Today we're cutting out all our pieces, then basting and quilting our panels. A few notes on today's assignment:

🩷 I prefer to use Odif 505 basting spray to hold my layers together, but safety pins also work great!

🩷 The video shows me using a Hera Marker to mark my quilting lines. I love to use a  Hera Marker because it makes impressions instead of ink lines.

🩷 Even though we've already basted, sewing the layers together 1/8" from one of the edges keeps the layers from shifting as they are quilted. I choose a side that I can start most of my quilting lines from and sew along that edge before starting the quilting.

🩷 For machine quilting, I like to increase my stitch length a little (from 2.5 up to 3.5ish), but I use the same thread and needle as all of my general sewing.

🩷 In this video, after sewing diagonal lines in one direction, I used the Hera Marker to mark lines in the opposite direction for a diamond pattern (use the 60° line on your mat or ruler for diamonds).

🩷 Essen Pouch Sew Along Day 2 🩷

Today we're preparing the Handles and Binding Strips and finishing up the Quilted + Vinyl Panel. A couple notes for today's assignment:

🩷 Remember to attach the Bindings to the wrong side of the fabric/vinyl first. Most vinyls don't have a "right" or "wrong" side, so just designate one side as the front so all the Bindings are finished on the same side.

🩷 When attaching the Vinyl Panel to the Quilted Panel, make sure the Zipper Bindings (the wider strips) on the Vinyl Panels are facing away from the Quilted Panel.

🩷 Place the Vinyl Binding underneath the Quilted Panel Binding and overlap those Overlap Bindings (see why I called them that? 😜). You want them overlapped just enough to be able to top stitch the outer edge of the Quilted Binding and catch vinyl (instead of the vinyl's Binding) underneath.

🩷 Essen Pouch Sew Along Day 3 🩷

Today, we're installing the zipper! A few notes about the assignment:

🩷 When lining up the zipper to sew it onto the first Zipper Binding, leave most of the extra length of the zipper at the bottom (as shown in the pattern and this video). The extra length helps a lot when sewing the second side of the zipper on.

🩷 Sew about 1/8" away from the edge of the Binding, catching the zipper tape underneath. Sew slowly, making sure the zipper teeth stay the same distance away from the presser foot the whole time .

🩷 I use the standard presser foot that came with my machine, but many people prefer to use a zipper foot. Play around with the presser feet you have and use whichever one feels most comfortable.

🩷 Essen Pouch Sew Along Day 4 🩷

Today, we're adding the End Bindings and cutting our boxy corners. A few notes on today's assignment:

🩷 Remember to turn your pouch inside out before sewing it shut. 

🩷 In the video, I show two ideas for sewing on vinyl. I have a non-stick presser foot that fits my machine (Juki TL2000). It really helps so the presser foot doesn't stick to the vinyl (you can find the link to this inexpensive foot in my Amazon Faves-link in profile). You can also use a small strip of paper in between the presser foot and the vinyl and/or the feed dogs and the vinyl. Sew right through the paper then when you're finished with that seam, bend and tear off the paper. 🙌

🩷 When marking the boxy corners, remember to mark from the seam instead of the outside edge of the binding sides. This will make the boxy corner square.

🩷 Essen Pouch Sew Along Day 5 🩷

We're finishing our pouches! A few notes on today's assignment:

🩷 After sewing the first side of the Boxy Corner Binding on, I like to trim the bulkiest areas of the seam (particularly where the Handle and End Binding meet up), so the Boxy Corner Binding can wrap around the edge better.

🩷 If your machine struggles going through the thick seams at the end, here are a few tips that might help:
🩷 Use a jeans needle. They are made to be heavy duty for going through tough fabric.
🩷 Use your handwheel to gently guide the needle through the layers. 
🩷 Before sewing on the binding, make a few more stitch lines through the seam allowance area of the boxy corner to really flatten it out.
🩷 It might sound funny, but you can use a hammer or mallet to flatten out the seam! Hammer the layers, especially where the End Binding and Handle meet, and your machine might have an easier time with it.

How to easily get perfect points on your patchwork panel! 🙌 Have you tried this method?

💛 Start with lightweight fusible interfacing (Pellon SF101 is shown here) and some precut squares (2.5" squares from the Simply Delightful collection).
💛 Place the squares, then gently press them to adhere to the interfacing. No need to make sure the squares are placed absolutely perfect!
💛 Fold over the first column and sew with a 1/4" seam. Continue on for the remainder of the columns.
💛 Barely trim off the end of the seam allowance (where the fold is), then press open. Repeat with each of the seams. Note: this is the first time I've done the pressing this way. I LOVE how flat the panel is with the open seams, but it does take longer than pressing to one side.
💛 Now, move on to the rows. Fold the first row over, sew with a 1/4" seam, trim the very edge of the seam, and press open.
💛 Admire the perfectly matched points on the squares! It's like magic and works every time!! 🎉

Holland Pouch Sew Along Day 1

Let's baste and quilt our fabric!

🩷 I prefer to use Odif 505 basting spray to hold my layers together, but safety pins also work great!

🩷 Even though we've already basted, sewing the layers together 1/8" from one of the edges keeps the layers from shifting as they are quilted. I choose a side that I can start most of my quilting lines from and sew along that edge before starting the quilting.

🩷 The video shows me using a Hera Marker to mark my quilting lines. I love to use a  Hera Marker because it makes impressions instead of ink lines.

🩷 For machine quilting, I like to increase my stitch length a little (from 2.5 up to 3.5ish), but I use the same thread and needle as all of my general sewing.

🩷 In this video, after sewing diagonal lines in one direction, I used the Hera Marker to mark lines in the opposite direction for a diamond pattern (use the 60° line on your mat or ruler for diamonds).

Holland Pouch Sew Along Day 2

We're getting our Handles and Bindings prepped!

A few notes about today:

🩷 The Bindings, as described in the pattern, are very straightforward (just press in half the long way), but I'd like to share an alternate way to do the End Bindings and Boxy Corner Bindings to lessen the bulk in the last few seams of the pouch. This will particularly help if your machine isn't as powerful and struggles with thick seams. You can still choose to complete them as written in the pattern or you can try this other option.
 
🩷 For the Bindings:
The Zipper Bindings won't have any change: still press the Zipper Bindings in half the long way and set aside.
For the End Bindings and Boxy Corner Bindings, cut these Bindings down from 2 ½" wide to 1 ½" wide (keep them the same length). Then we're going to press them like the instructions for the Handles. Fold in half the long way, press. Unfold, then fold each long edge into the center folded line and press. Refold at center folded line and press again. This method is called a single fold binding and, while a little more complicated than the original double fold binding (just pressed in half once), the single fold binding results in less bulky seams.
 
🩷 Note: the terms “single fold binding” and “double fold binding” refer to how many layers of fabric are covering the raw edge that you are binding. So although the “single fold binding” is prepared by folding and pressing more than once, there is only one layer of fabric covering the very edge of the surface we're binding. Likewise, for a “double fold binding”, it is only pressed once, but there are two layers of fabric covering the raw edge of the surface we're binding. The naming convention is a little confusing at first, but makes sense when you know what the name is describing. :)

Holland Pouch Sew Along Day 4

If you want to try the single fold binding method as described in the Day 2 email, then today's the day where we're veering from the pattern just a little.

As a reminder: the End and Boxy Corner Bindings, as written in the pattern, are the simplest way to bind raw edges, however, they do create a bit of bulk. So on Day 2, I shared a way to cut and press the End Bindings and Boxy Corner Bindings to help lessen that bulk. To alter the End Bindings and Boxy Corner Bindings to do the single fold binding method, they need to be trimmed to 1 ½" wide (keep them the same length), and pressed in the same manner as the Handles were pressed. 

🩷 After closing the ends of the pouch (remember to turn it inside out first!), trim off any excess zipper and then attach the End Bindings.

🩷 If attaching the End Bindings using the method in the pattern, sew them on just like the Zipper Bindings.

🩷 If attaching the End Bindings trimmed to 1.5" wide using the alternative method, open up one Emd Binding and place the raw edge, right sides together, on the end of the panel. Sew with a 1/4" seam (this seam will be just to the outside of the fold line).

🩷 Fold the Binding at the two outside fold lines, wrong sides together, and wrap the Binding up and around the panel's raw edge. Sew into place by top stitching along the edge of the Binding.

🩷 When marking the Boxy Corners, remember to marl from the seam line on the End Binding side, not the outer edge! This will create a square Boxy Corner and help things line up for tomorrow's assignment.

Holland Pouch Sew Along Day 5

We're finishing our pouches today! 🎉

🩷 All that's left to do today is insert the Handles, close up out Boxy Corners and and the Boxy Corner Bindings. 

🩷 I show two different ways to do the Bindings in the video. The first is the way it's written in the pattern and the second is the alternative single fold binding method. If your machine struggles with bulk, I'd suggest cutting the Bindings down to 1.5" wide, pressing them like the Handles and using this alternative method. 😊

A few extra tips if your machine has a hard time with these last few thick seams:
🩷 Try a jeans needle. They are thicker and stronger and might help your machine navigate all the layers better.
🩷 If your machine has the option, lower the pressure on the presser foot.
🩷 Before sewing on the Boxy Corner Binding, make some extra stitch lines in the seam allowance of the Boxy Corners. This will help flatten that area.
🩷 It might sound funny, but you can use a hammer or mallet to flatten out the seam! Hammer the layers, especially where the End Binding and Handle are, and your machine might be happier with it.
🩷 The final top stitching seam on the Binding can be finished by hand if your machine can't get through the layers.

🩷 Once all four Boxy Corners are finished, you can turn your pouch right side out through the zipper. I've found that the process of adding the Boxy Corner Bindings usually creases the Handles, so I like to iron them to make them look crisp again.

Alpen Belt Bag Sew Along Day 2

A few tips for today:

❤️ When sewing the Strap back into itself (step 10 on page 6), you can either tuck the end of the Strap under to conceal the raw edge (and prevent fraying), or of you have polyester webbing, you can carefully melt the cut edge with a flame to seal it.

❤️ As stated in the pattern, the 1.5 yd of webbing should accommodate a cross-body fit for women's sizes small through extra large. If unsure on the strap size or if using the bag around your waist instead, a longer or shorter piece can be used for the 46" length. Alternatively, you can wait until the very end of the pattern to finish the Long Strap (steps 8-10 on page 6). Still add the Strap Tabs to the Long Strap piece, but leave the Strap Slider and Swivel Hook off until the rest of the bag is completed and the Strap length can be tested.

The Hemingway Pouch - 5 Ways in 5 Days!

This week I'm sharing five unique variations of the Hemingway Pouch to show how easy it is to change up the look of this versatile pattern. 🥰

Day #2: Use vinyl!

To make the Hemingway Pouch even faster (who knew it was possible?!?), skip the quilting and use vinyl. A vinyl Hemingway Pouch also has the added benefit of easily seeing inside! Perfect for keeping items contained in a purse or backpack. 🙌

A few notes on making a vinyl Hemingway Pouch:

For this small size Hemingway Pouch, instead of putting the binding on the inside of the pouch, I switched it to the outside. These little pouches can be hard to turn right side out at the end, and with the stiff vinyl, it makes it even more difficult. Adding the binding on the outside quickly finishes off the pouch without having to turn it. Yay!

If using vinyl, you can also forgo the binding entirely if you'd like! Since the vinyl won't fray like fabric, finishing off those raw edges isn't necessary. 

You'll notice that I show a different presser foot in the video. That's a non-stick presser foot that I purchased for my sewing machine that works really well for sewing with vinyl. If you also own a Juki TL2000 or TL2010, you can check out the exact presser foot I have in my Amazon product recommendations -there's a link in my profile (it's usually selling for under $5!).

Day #3: Add a quilt block!

Add a little something extra to your Hemingway Pouch by incorporating a quilt block. It's an easy way to make it ultra-personalized and unique! For this large size Hemingway Pouch, I used the Tall Tales quilt block from @katebasti and now I have the perfect book sleeve! 

A note about the quilting: I started by marking and quilting 60° diagonal lines (shown in the video), then used the 60° line on my ruler to mark and quilt lines going the opposite direction. Let's make a zippered heart pouch!

This little zippered heart pouch was so fast and fun to make--they would be perfect for gifting to kids, grandkids, friends, etc. on Valentine's Day!

A few notes: 
🩷 I added Pellon SF101 (a lightweight fusible interfacing) to the wrong sides of the fabric for a little extra structure. 
🩷 The paper heart was drawn freehand and was about 5.5" tall x 6" wide. You could definitely go bigger in size, but I don't think I'd try much smaller, as then there won't really be room to put things in the pouch.
🩷 When sewing the heart layers together, I'd recommend backstitching over the zipper so when you turn the pouch right side out, the stitches across the zipper teeth don't pop (ask me how I know 🙄 😆). Then leave a small opening to turn the pouch right side out.
🩷 I stitched the opening (that I used to turn the pouch right side out) closed by hand. I chose a matching @aurifilthread color, and while my stitches are far from perfect, it really finishes the pouch off nicely.
